Properties ¶

Starting from the histogram of the following image:

table
img, treated = chestXRAY.show_array_image(filename)

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
major_ticks = np.arange(0, 255, 20)
minor_ticks = np.arange(0, 255, 5)

ax.set_xticks(major_ticks)
ax.set_xticks(minor_ticks, minor=True)
ax.grid()
ax.grid(which='minor', alpha=0.4)
n, bins, patches = ax.hist(img.flatten(), bins=range(256))

There are two areas for improvement:

  • Exposure to the image
  • Light distribution

Our objective will be to equalize the image so that we can bring out the shades of gray as much as possible.

To do this, we will simply stretch the histogram using the following formula:

Either the intensity:

$[I_{min}, I_{max}] \in [0, 255] $

For x, y the plane coordinates of a pixel, apply the formula:

$$ I' (x, y) = \frac{255\times(I(x,y) - I_{min})}{I_{max} - I_{min}} $$

For the improvement of the contrast, we will try to distribute the gray levels evenly on the axis : $I \in [0, 255] $

We therefore apply the following normal distribution:

$$ I' (x, y) =\lfloor 255. \sum_{i=0}^{I(x,y)} p_i\rfloor $$

In order to facilitate the implementation of these solutions, we used the solutions autocontrast and equalizeof the ImagesOps module of PIL

Post treatment result ¶

In order to standardize the size of the image without loss of information, we have chosen to crop the image by the center, For this, we retrieve the median size of the entire dataset as a reference value, then we crop or enlarged equally each image.

Statistical processing ¶

Image size¶

We have chosen to crop images of different sizes towards the center, in order to limit the loss of information. However, with large disparities in sizes, the loss of information can be quite significant. When we analyze the data set according to the size criteria:

In [9]:
import pandas as pd

dataframe_height = chestXRAY.show_height_total_data()
dataframe_width = chestXRAY.show_width_total_data()
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2)

dataframe_height.sort_values(by=['height']).groupby(['height']).size().reset_index(name='counts')\
    .plot(x='height', y='counts' ,kind='bar', ax=ax1, xticks=[], width=1.0)

dataframe_width.sort_values(by=['width']).groupby(['width']).size().reset_index(name='counts')\
    .plot(x='width', y='counts' ,kind='bar', ax=ax2, xticks=[],  width=1.0)

table = pd.concat([chestXRAY.show_height_stats(), chestXRAY.show_width_stats()], ignore_index=True)
table
Out[9]:
Total Median Weight Median Height Quantile min 5% Quantile max 95% Ignore (%)
0 5214 840 840 367.9 1642.0 18
1 5214 1232 1232 679.0 1906.0 7

This eliminates the extremum data of the curve, in order to limit the parasitic data as much as possible. Arbitrarily, we filter the values beyond outside the 5% and above the 95% of the quartiles.
